ted_reshetiloff(-at-)yahoo.com writes:

Has  anyone had experience driving their bus on the beach? Headed to ocean 
camping  this weekend and there is an area where trucks can be on the beach. 
They have  air lines for putting air back in tires as most let air out to 
go in the sand.  Will a bus handle the soft sand or do you need 4wd? Do I let 
air out and if so  how much?



hello Ted  driving on sand can be very hard, very easy to get  stuck.carry 
a tow chain or strap. make sure your CV boots are in good  shape,  Lower the 
air pressure to about 10-15 psi bigger balder tires work  best  stay out of 
the deep dry sand. stay in the other tire tracks.   next to the water the 
sand is pretty hard and easy to drive on.  I use to  take my splitty out on 
Ocacoke a lot. watch out and don't let the tides catch  you out there.  I saw 
a brand new Jeep once get caught out on a sandbar .  by the time they got 
it out it was ruined  later  mark  d
